annotation.TEXT: Here's another multi-coin block. There are plenty of them in this hack. I'm probably not gonna waste too much time with these. Maybe I'll just get 9 coins from most of them and then move on.
Yuugi takes the place of the Hammer Bros., and there's a 1-up in this brick here.
Huh. This pattern looks familiar. Does that mean there's another star here?
Oh, yeah. You probably noticed that the super mushroom was likewise replaced with a "9-square" (Is there a symbol for that?), and that Letty appeared when I became "super". That's cool.
21-life combo! Alright, I typically like to just get one 1-up combo off of this trick and then move on.
Alright, Yuugi's gone, so now to...

Alright, now there is no real boss here, just another Yuugi. However, even after you get past her, watch out, because the fire generator doesn't stop until you stomp the "B" on the other end of this bridge.
This star should make things easy for a while.
Also, for some reason, if you just flatout run through that passage after ducking into it while big, you'll pass through the coins without collecting them, so duck periodically to collect them.
Yes, there's a lot of pipe entering in stage 1-1, and a lot of blatant level edits of the original SMB's bonus rooms.
I'm pretty sure none of the pipes in this level go anywhere.

By the way, I notice that this level mainly uses the original SMB's castle music. So, I wonder why they didn't just leave the original SMB's water music alone instead of replacing it with the star theme...
Nuts. I was hoping to clobber both Nues with that Kisume.

And here's another water zone. Just like in the original SMB, there's your usual pipe-residing enemy in this entry pipe that is invisible, but you can shoot it for 200 points (or touch it and get hurt if you're a baka).

Alright, I'm now at "Crown-O" lives, and that's the letter "O", not the number zero. So, I've currently got 34 lives. Also, I have no idea what happened to the stage number. For some reason, it's showing a weird graphic where a "4" should be, but this is indeed 1-4.
Watch out for the Yuugis here. Man, my projectiles' tendency to bounce into the brick ledges will make this tricky...
There's no choice but to go down this pipe.
Alright!
Now, I'm probably gonna be bonking my head on many brick ceilings in an effort to find more secrets that I may have missed, but I won't spend too long doing so.
Watch out for the Bullet Ichirin as you hit this vine block here. Oh, and don't even think about trying to jump across that abyss to the right.
No, it's actually a 1-up this time!
You probably won't be able to hit something on the ground right next to you, and low ceilings can be a problem, but you can more easily target midair enemies in most cases.
Now, unfortunately, it doesn't look like 1-2 has been edited at all. Oh, well. Let's just double kill these Nues and get some more ice cream.
Watch out for Koishis sticking their heads out of the bridges too.
Umm... Yeah. That was a demo alright!
The Fire Bar's graphics are unchanged, except they're green now. Also, I could totally go over the top of the level, but I want to play it the normal way.
Actually, it doesn't look like it. Instead we get Rin again. Also, I like how the mushroom platforms have become UFOs here.
Hello, and welcome to my 999th (or ⑨⑨⑨th) video! Now obviously, I've gotta do something Cirno related, and I've decided on this SMB hack, Final Strikyu, which stars Cirno!
Alright, 1-3 starts me off with some ice cream, and more blatant level edits!

Whoa, this part's tricky. Now, it is possible to glitch yourself through the pipe here above the cannon, and it'll result in you skipping part of the level, but it's very tricky to do, and I want to play this normally.
You can break the ceiling blocks here, and... huh. I didn't know that 1-up was there. I have played through this hack before, so I already know of some secrets, but I guess not every secret.
But, if you're ascending, you'll usually be the one to get hurt, unless you're hitting the top of certain enemies like parakoopas, which allow you to stomp them on your way up anyway.
Watch out for this Satori.
Aw, she (very intelligently) retreated there.
However, if you're going to do that, break a few columns of ceiling blocks on the left like this, then slowly scroll the screen over.

Alright, I'm at "Crown-T" lives (which is 39), and I'm entering... Stage 2-green block with a vertical zigzag in it? I don't know what's causing the stage number to screw up like that, but I am actually entering 2-2, of course.
I don't think any pipes in this level lead anywhere, but I just gotta check them anyway.
And, we're at the goal. So, let's get 6 fireworks this time!
It would've been neat if the invincibility star was actually made to look like Star Sapphire, but I think the standard starshape is more fitting.
Stop! No more hammer time!
Be careful of that Fire Bar and the Ichirins that'll suddenly appear here as you go to use the springboard.
Now, I don't think there's a way to reach the right-most ⑨-blocks on the top here. There's no hidden block to reach them with that I can find.
Alright, I'm just gonna rush in there.

Now there's an oddity in SMB's programming regarding coins sitting on blocks. If a coin is sitting on a ? block or a brick that contains an item, and you hit that block without getting the coin first, you'll only get the coin.
Entering 2-3... Will it have flying Cheepo Parsees?
Whoa, Satori takes the place of Blooper here! However, the altered trajectory of my shots makes it easier to shoot her down.
Oh, hey! Rin decided to come back! Let's shoot her down now!
Well, this room looks strikingly similar to a particular bonus room of SMB, but there are some differences, such as the enemies and the hidden block here.
Snap! +1000! Unlike in SMB Crossover, I'm perfectly okay with breaking balance lifts here, as long as I see a place to safely jump to, because I know my jump button press will be acknowledged!
Whoa, geez! That was close!
Yep! But, does the brick above this row of ⑨-blocks contain multiple coins again?
Man, I'm starting to feel a little bad for all these Kisumes I'm knocking around...
There's more ice cream, in case you're still hungry.
Alright!
Oh, but the Parsees only appeared briefly, and were quickly replaced with Bowser's fire.
Hmm... I guess Rin's not coming back, probably due to the fish generator. I'm fine with that.
This hack's got that Beloved Tomboyish Daughter music just like that ⑨ hack I played a while back.
Whoa, that was close. I got a little lucky with that Kisume stomp there.
And, just like before, I see no way to hit the right-most ⑨-blocks on top here.
Ooh, I like star.
Yep, here's the multi-coin block you were probably expecting to see in this room.
Ooh, check this out! Yep, you can totally do this right here!
And again I take out Yuugi instantly. Those Yuugis would've been a much greater threat if I didn't have firepower.
Oh, and be aware of the Nue up there if you go over the top.

Be careful of the Fire Bar and Ichirin cannon combinations here. Make sure you duck jump here, because for some reason, if you do a standing jump and hit the bottom of a Fire Bar hub block, you'll get hurt, but you won't get hurt that way if you're duck jumping (or if you're small).
However, unlike in ⑨, the digits in my score, etc. can show numbers other than 0 or 9. Yeah, this is not really a joke hack like ⑨ was.
You can never have enough ice cream.
Bah! How did I let that happen? Well, the ice cream will give me Letty back, but I'm still gonna be without firepower for now.
Heh. I like the number of coins I'm holding right now.

Fourth blatant edit room, ahoy! You can probably guess that that lone brick above the pipe contains a power up. At least it's easy to reach even if you're super in this case. (In the original SMB, it takes a tricky duck-jump to hit the block if you're big.)
So, yeah. This hack only has two worlds. And, I'm not going to play through the harder quest. I believe it pretty much works the same way as in SMB.
Alright, time for a sky bonus area, with the clouds made up of Unzans.
This is the third obvious bonus room rip-off, and that means there should be a power up to find here. Hopefully you got here "super"!
If the block in question also had a coin (like these), this gyps you out of one coin, but if the block had a different item, you don't get that item (I don't think that happens in this hack, though).
Wow, that Yuugi didn't last long.
Alright, it's final boss time, against Utsuho!
Or, better yet, let's grab this ice cream and shoot her down!
(Oh, and there was also a star similarly hidden in a column of bricks just before the first bridge section that I forgot to pick up. Oops. Oh, well.)
No warp zone or minus world here, because the screen stops scrolling, so just enter the pipe and head for the goal.
Yep, this room's hardly changed from the original SMB.
I kind of wish this hack used different music for the water level instead of a slightly modified star theme. Would something like "Lunate Elf" have been too difficult to put into this hack?
Yes! I avoided being glitch hit! Now, once again, jump left when you emerge here to reveal one more hidden block to allow you to reach the final power up in the game!
Yes! Cirno and Letty love ice cream!
Oh, and we've gotta do the vine dance at least once!
Awesome!
Whoops, I failed to check that pipe. Well, I'm sure it didn't lead anywhere. (But if I'm wrong, let me know.)
So, is this the castle that Daiyousei is being kept in? We'll find out today!
We've done it! We've rescued Daiyousei! Why she was being held captive in the first place is beyond me, but whatever.
They can be shot down, but don't try to stomp them (because they're actually Spinies). Also, Rin can be shot down as well, but stomping her (or anything else) is impossible in a water level.
Now, upon landing here, watch out, because there are Ichirin cannons around.
"Crown-V" lives. That's 41.
Ha! That Yuugi was blasted immediately! ...Oh, nuts! Flying Parsees! And I don't have a star available here! Just another 1-up!
Man, I'm sucking at hitting these Koishis right now for some reason.
If you can't shoot something because it's too close to you on the ground, just jump over it (or on it if it's stompable).
I'm so glad the star's invincibility duration is normal in this hack, unlike in ⑨, where it's pathetically short.
GAAAMMMEEE!!!
Alright, we're in the castle now, and just to make sure you don't leave or try to do some sort of wall climbing trick, there are hidden coin blocks right here.
Well, that wasn't hard. If you can shoot her, the usual five shots will do the trick! Otherwise, it's the usual evasion tactics that you'd use to get past Bowser in SMB.
Demo count: Demoception
And, after exiting that sky bonus area, I end up in another one. Yes, these are basically edits of the two different sky bonus areas from the original SMB.
Rin's back. Better be careful.
Just like last time, jump left as soon as you emerge here to find a hidden block, not only to reach the power up above, but to attack Rin too.
Whoa, careful.
Well, that was unfortunate. So, it appears that I've rescued Nazrin (who I guess is on our side).
Score!

For some reason, we fall out of the sky here instead of emerging from the pipe. Ah, but yes, this is the goal, and the flagpole and fireworks still work the same as in the original SMB. Let's try for 6!

Yeah, there's a Kisume there, waiting to ambush you. If you rush forward, you'll almost certainly get hit (and die if you're small), and if you break the ceiling blocks in a poor fashion, you could trap yourself and be forced to wait until time runs out. Yeah, this part isn't very well-designed.
Now, if you jump to the left as soon as you emerge here, you'll find a hidden coin block, which will let you reach the power up above.

Oh, but what's this? Looks like 1-2 has been edited after all, starting a couple screens in. It's almost like 2-3 of SMB now, complete with flying Cheepo Parsees! (At least I think they're Parsees...)
That was a neat stomp. In the original SMB, it doesn't matter how you collide with a stompable enemy if you're descending-- you will stomp it.
You can safely duck under this extra-long Fire Bar here. Just watch out for other foes like this Yamame.

More bridges and flying Parsees. But, there's a star in this column of bricks here (which still looks like a star, though a hollowed-out one, like a bomb part from TH12 and TH14), which'll let you blaze through safely!

Whoa, I thought that was a power up at first, not a 1-up! Still managed to get it, though! Now, it is possible to jump off of the elevators to go over the ceiling here and skip part of the level (and starting from the 1-up block works best for this), but I'm once again gonna play this normally.
Whoa, that was close.

Alright, I'm fully powered up again, so let's try for a perfect in this area. Oh, and continue to watch for Ichirins. They can't truly kill you here, but they can rob you of your power up and keep you from collecting coins.
If you want to hit all of the blocks here, do it exactly like this, or the screen scroll could mess up that plan.
Let's just watch this demo first...
Sky bonus perfects: 1
Sometimes I just have trouble getting the angle right on my shots.
And, I'm looking for Daichan, which I assume means Daiyousei. Alright, now for world 2!
Alright, that's enough of that. Let's grab this 1-up hidden in the ceiling, which takes the form of a 9 in a square.
Also, this is quite clearly a blatant edit of the water bonus room from 5-2 and 6-2 of the original SMB.
I believe that Buzzy there is Yamame. Also, I'm running low on time, so let's enter the fifth and final blatant level edit room of 1-1.
Nice!

Alright, now watch out, because there are Ichirins flying around through here. However, interestingly, if you die to an enemy in a sky bonus area, you won't actually lose a life, and will instead be teleported out of the sky area as if you finished it normally.
I kind of want this power up, so yeah, I'm gonna miss some coins while getting it.
Also, there's an unreachable Nue on the roof for some reason.
That's one level down. Oh, by the way, in case you weren't paying attention, you start this hack with 9 lives, just like in ⑨.
Okay, now in this area, you're probably meant to only be able to reach the coins up there if you're small. But, a well-aimed duck-jump can get you in if you're big.
And just like in the original SMB, 2-2 is a water level. Oh, and we've got Rin up above dropping zombie fairies down here.

Whoa, that's a big Fire Bar. And the pipe to the next area is right there. However, there is a nasty glitch here. If the Fire Bar overlaps you while you're entering the pipe, it will still actually hit you. This is fatal if you're small (and will keep you from shooting down the final boss if you're big). So, you've gotta try to enter the pipe quickly while the Fire Bar is far away!
Okay, let's get this party started!
Yes!
LOL at me torturing this poor Kisume. Oh, yeah. Nearly every enemy is graphically changed to look like a Touhou character.
Whoops, gypped myself out of a coin there. Oh, well.
Now, just like in ⑨, the fireballs' trajectory is different. They go up into the air a bit when you fire them, but not quite as high as in ⑨. Also, they bounce pretty high as well.
And, we're done. Yep, that was totally an edit of the original SMB's 2-2, although Rin's presence at the beginning was certainly unusual.
Ah, yes. I thought I remembered there being a 1-up hidden there.
Oh, that poor Kisume, and I can still fry her while she's jammed in the bricks like that.
Whoa. Yes, that was a Podoboo, which I think was Kogasa, trying to surprise me! Unfortunately for her, I had star power!

But, I will show that you can only choose between worlds 1 and 2 with the B button here. Well, I hope you all enjoyed watching me play through Final Strikyu for my ⑨⑨⑨th video! What do I have planned for video #1000? Find out next time!
Oh, and don't even consider trying to hit those ⑨-blocks in the lava down there. But, you can still at least stand on them if you want to.
That's got it.
Whoa! I just totally glitched through a piece of land there! I must've hit it at just the right angle.
Oh, baka! I hit the flag too early.
Parsees serve as the fishies down here too.
Oh, and in case you didn't notice, the taller Ichirin Cannons have Murasas as their bases. That's a neat graphical detail.
